# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: self-sovereign-identity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] A **decentralized identifier (DID)** is a type of globally unique identifier that enables an entity to be identified in a manner that is verifiable, persistent (as long as the DID controller desires), and does not require the use of a centralized registry.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] DIDs enable a new model of decentralized digital identity that is often referred to as a self-sovereign identity (SSI).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] The DIDs are an important component of decentralized web applications.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] A decentralized identifier resolves (points) to a **DID document**, a set of data describing the DID subject, including mechanisms, such as cryptographic public keys, that the DID subject or a DID delegate can use to authenticate itself and prove its association with the DID.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] Just as there are many different types of URIs, all of which conform to the URI standard, there are many different types of **DID methods**, all of which must conform to the DID standard.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] The W3C DID Working Group maintains a registry of DID methods.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] A DID identifies any subject (e.g., a person, organization, thing, data model, abstract entity, etc.) that the controller of the DID decides that it identifies.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] DIDs are designed to enable the controller of a DID to prove control over it and to be implemented independently of any centralized registry, identity provider, or certificate authority.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] DIDs are URIs that associate a DID subject with a DID document.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] Each DID document can express cryptographic material, verification methods, and service endpoints to enable trusted interactions associated with the DID subject.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] A DID document might contain additional semantics about the subject that it identifies.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] A DID document might also contain the DID subject itself (e.g. a data model).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] National efforts include the European Digital Identity (EUDI) Wallet as a part of eIDAS 2.0 in the European Union, and China Real-Name Decentralized Identifier System (China RealDID) under China's Ministry of Public Security.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] The AT Protocol and applications powered by the protocol such as Bluesky use DIDs for their identity system in order to give users full control over their identity, including where their data is stored.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] The protocol uses its own DID method, did:plc, as well as a general domain-based method with did:web.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] Persona is an identity verification company founded in 2018.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] Its product consists of uploading a government-issued ID and potentially taking a selfie to confirm the user's identity and give them a DID identity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] The service is used by the LinkedIn professional networking site, the Discord and Reddit social media networks, the Roblox video game platform, and the OpenAI artificial intelligence company.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] Polygon ID is a privacy-focused digital identity solution developed by Polygon, a blockchain scaling platform.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] It leverages zero-knowledge proofs (ZKPs) to allow users to verify specific aspects of their identity—such as age or residency—without revealing underlying personal data.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] This enables secure and private interactions with services that require identity verification, such as financial platforms, voting systems, or DAO governance, while preserving user anonymity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] Polygon ID is already being explored by governments and organizations seeking compliant and privacy-preserving identity systems in Web3 environments.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] The W3C DID Working Group developed a specification for decentralized identifiers to standardize the core architecture, data model, and representation of DIDs.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] The W3C approved the DID 1.0 specification as a W3C Recommendation on July 19, 2022.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/decentralized-identifier] The Decentralized Identity Foundation (DIF) published a Dynamic Traveler Profile Generation Specification in June 2023, for use cases in the travel industry.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] A **digital identity** is data stored on computer systems relating to an individual, organization, application, or device.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] For individuals, it involves the collection of personal data that is essential for facilitating automated access to digital services, confirming one's identity on the internet, and allowing digital systems to manage interactions between different parties.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] It is a component of a person's social identity in the digital realm, often referred to as their online identity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Digital identities are composed of the full range of data produced by a person's activities on the internet, which may include usernames and passwords, search histories, dates of birth, social security numbers, and records of online purchases.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] When such personal information is accessible in the public domain, it can be used by others to piece together a person's offline identity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Furthermore, this information can be compiled to construct a data double, a comprehensive profile created from a person's scattered digital footprints across various platforms.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] These profiles enable personalized experiences on the internet and within different digital services.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] A critical problem in cyberspace is knowing who one is interacting with.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Using only static identifiers such as passwords and email, there is no way to precisely determine the identity of a person in cyberspace because this information can be stolen or used by many individuals acting as one.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Digital identity based on dynamic entity relationships captured from behavioral history across multiple websites and mobile apps can verify and authenticate identity with up to 95% accuracy.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] By comparing a set of entity relationships between a new event (e.g., login) and past events, a pattern of convergence can verify or authenticate the identity as legitimate whereas divergence indicates an attempt to mask an identity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Data used for digital identity is generally encrypted using a one-way hash, thereby avoiding privacy concerns.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Because it is based on behavioral history, a digital identity is very hard to fake or steal.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] A digital identity may also be referred to as a *digital subject* or *digital entity*.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] They are the digital representation of a set of claims made by one party about itself or another person, group, thing, or concept.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] A digital twin which is also commonly known as a data double or virtual twin is a secondary version of the original user's data.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Which is used both as a way to observe what said user does on the internet as well as customize a more personalized internet experience.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Due to the collection of personal data, there have been many social, political, and legal controversies tying into data doubles.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] While in manufacturing and other multi-organization environments, digital identity is used to enable secure interactions between separate organizations.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] For a secure federated digital thread, participating systems rely on verified digital identities to authenticate organizations before exchanging product lifecycle data, supporting trust and controlled data sharing across organizational boundaries.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The attributes of a digital identity are acquired and contain information about a user, such as medical history, purchasing behavior, bank balance, age, and so on.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Preferences retain a user's choices such as favorite brand of shoes, and preferred currency.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Traits are features of the user that are inherent, such as eye color, nationality, and place of birth.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Although attributes of a user can change easily, traits change slowly, if at all.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] A digital identity also has entity relationships derived from the devices, environment, and locations from which an individual is active on the Internet.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Some of those include facial recognition, fingerprints, photos, and so many more personal attributes/preferences.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Digital identities can be issued through digital certificates.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] These certificates contain data associated with a user and are issued with legal guarantees by recognized certification authorities.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] In order to assign a digital representation to an entity, the attributing party must trust that the claim of an attribute (such as name, location, role as an employee, or age) is correct and associated with the person or thing presenting the attribute.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Conversely, the individual claiming an attribute may only grant selective access to its information (e.g., proving identity in a bar or PayPal authentication for payment at a website).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] In this way, digital identity is better understood as a particular viewpoint within a mutually-agreed relationship than as an objective property.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Physical authentication techniques include iris scanning, fingerprinting, and voice recognition; those techniques are called *biometrics*.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The use of both static identifiers (e.g., username and password) and personal unique attributes (e.g., biometrics) is called *multi-factor authentication* and is more secure than the use of one component alone.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Whilst technological progress in authentication continues to evolve, these systems do not prevent aliases from being used.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] To address this, proof of personhood protocols such as World ID by Tool for Humanity, Humanode, and BrightID are increasingly employed to verify that a digital identity belongs to a unique, living human, effectively preventing the creation of duplicate accounts or automated Sybil identities.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] In blockchain systems, account-based identity approaches include ERC-725, a draft Ethereum standard for smart-contract accounts with generic data storage and execution, and LUKSO Universal Profiles, which use ERC-725/LSP0 to combine profile metadata with account permissions.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The introduction of strong authentication for online payment transactions within the European Union now links a verified person to an account, where such person has been identified in accordance with statutory requirements prior to account being opened.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Verifying a person opening an account online typically requires a form of device binding to the credentials being used.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] This verifies that the device that stands in for a person on the Internet is actually the individual's device and not the device of someone simply claiming to be the individual.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The concept of reliance authentication makes use of pre-existing accounts, to piggy back further services upon those accounts, providing that the original source is reliable.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] An example of reliance authentication is PayPal's verification method.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Consider the person who rents a car and checks into a hotel with a credit card.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The car rental and hotel company may request authentication that there is credit enough for an accident, or profligate spending on room service.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Thus a card may later be refused when trying to purchase an activity such as a balloon trip.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Though there is adequate credit to pay for the rental, the hotel, and the balloon trip, there is an insufficient amount to also cover the authorizations.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The actual charges are authorized after leaving the hotel and returning the car, which may be too late for the balloon trip.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Valid online authorization requires analysis of information related to the digital event including device and environmental variables.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] These are generally derived from the data exchanged between a device and a business server over the Internet.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Businesses use identity verification services to check whether a person has provided information associated with the identity of a real person.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] This is a form of electronic authentication.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Some websites with user accounts, such as social media services, offer account verification to show that an account is operated by a specific person.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Some decentralized identity verification systems, such as within the Fediverse and Mastodon, use a web standard microformat called `rel="me"`.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The `rel="me"` value is an HTML link relationship attribute used to indicate that two web resources represent the same person or entity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] It originated as part of early web microformats and has been used in decentralized identity systems to associate profiles and websites controlled by a single individual.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Digital identity requires digital identifiers—strings or tokens that are unique within a given scope (globally or locally within a specific domain, community, directory, application, etc.).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Identifiers may be classified as *omnidirectional* or *unidirectional*.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Omnidirectional identifiers are public and easily discoverable, whereas unidirectional identifiers are intended to be private and used only in the context of a specific identity relationship.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Identifiers may also be classified as *resolvable* or *non-resolvable*.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Resolvable identifiers, such as a domain name or email address, may be easily dereferenced into the entity they represent, or some current state data providing relevant attributes of that entity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Non-resolvable identifiers, such as a person's real name, or the name of a subject or topic, can be compared for equivalence but are not otherwise machine-understandable.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] There are many different schemes and formats for digital identifiers.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) and the internationalized version Internationalized Resource Identifier (IRI) are the standard for identifiers for websites on the World Wide Web.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] OpenID and Light-weight Identity are two web authentication protocols that use standard HTTP URIs (often called URLs).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] A Uniform Resource Name is a persistent, location-independent identifier assigned within the defined namespace.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Digital object architecture is a means of managing digital information in a network environment.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] In digital object architecture, a digital object has a machine and platform independent structure that allows it to be identified, accessed and protected, as appropriate.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] A digital object may incorporate not only informational elements, i.e., a digitized version of a paper, movie or sound recording, but also the unique identifier of the digital object and other metadata about the digital object.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The metadata may include restrictions on access to digital objects, notices of ownership, and identifiers for licensing agreements, if appropriate.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The Handle System is a general purpose distributed information system that provides efficient, extensible, and secure identifier and resolution services for use on networks such as the internet.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] It includes an open set of protocols, a namespace, and a reference implementation of the protocols.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The protocols enable a distributed computer system to store identifiers, known as handles, of arbitrary resources and resolve those handles into the information necessary to locate, access, contact, authenticate, or otherwise make use of the resources.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] This information can be changed as needed to reflect the current state of the identified resource without changing its identifier, thus allowing the name of the item to persist over changes of location and other related state information.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The original version of the Handle System technology was developed with support from the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] A new OASIS standard for abstract, structured identifiers, XRI (Extensible Resource Identifiers), adds new features to URIs and IRIs that are especially useful for digital identity systems.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] OpenID also supports XRIs, which are the basis for i-names.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Analysis are performed based on quantifiable metrics, such as transaction velocity, locale settings (or attempts to obfuscate), and user-input data (such as ship-to address).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Correlation and deviation are mapped to tolerances and scored, then aggregated across multiple entities to compute a transaction risk-score, which assess the risk posed to an organization.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Digital identity attributes exist within the context of ontologies.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The development of digital identity network solutions that can interoperate taxonomically diverse representations of digital identity is a contemporary challenge.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Free-tagging has emerged recently as an effective way of circumventing this challenge (to date, primarily with application to the identity of digital entities such as bookmarks and photos) by effectively flattening identity attributes into a single, unstructured layer.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] However, the organic integration of the benefits of both structured and fluid approaches to identity attribute management remains elusive.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Identity relationships within a digital network may include multiple identity entities.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] And if identity relationships are to reach beyond the context of a single, federated ontology of identity (see Taxonomies of identity above), identity attributes must somehow be matched across diverse ontologies.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The development of network approaches that can embody such integrated "compound" trust relationships is currently a topic of much debate in the blogosphere.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Integrated compound trust relationships allow, for example, entity A to accept an assertion or claim about entity B by entity C.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] C thus vouches for an aspect of B's identity to A.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] A key feature of "compound" trust relationships is the possibility of selective disclosure from one entity to another of locally relevant information.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] As an illustration of the potential application of selective disclosure, let us suppose a certain Diana wished to book a hire car without disclosing irrelevant personal information (using a notional digital identity network that supports compound trust relationships).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] As an adult, UK resident with a current driving license, Diana might have the UK's Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency vouch for her driving qualification, age, and nationality to a car-rental company without having her name or contact details disclosed.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Similarly, Diana's bank might assert just her banking details to the rental company.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Selective disclosure allows for appropriate privacy of information within a network of identity relationships.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] A classic form of networked digital identity based on international standards is the "White Pages".
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] An electronic white pages links various devices, like computers and telephones, to an individual or organization.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Various attributes such as X.509v3 digital certificates for secure cryptographic communications are captured under a schema, and published in an LDAP or X.500 directory.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Changes to the LDAP standard are managed by working groups in the IETF, and changes in X.500 are managed by the ISO.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The ITU did significant analysis of gaps in digital identity interoperability via the FGidm (ƒfocus group on identity management).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Implementations of X.500[2005] and LDAPv3 have occurred worldwide but are primarily located in major data centers with administrative policy boundaries regarding sharing of personal information.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Since combined X.500 [2005] and LDAPv3 directories can hold millions of unique objects for rapid access, it is expected to play a continued role for large scale secure identity access services.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] LDAPv3 can act as a lightweight standalone server, or in the original design as a TCP-IP based Lightweight Directory Access Protocol compatible with making queries to an X.500 mesh of servers which can run the native OSI protocol.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The ability to leverage and extend a networked digital identity is made more practicable by the expression of the level of trust associated with the given identity through a common Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] In digital rhetoric, digital identity is treated as a rhetorical construction shaped by the choices users make in how they represent themselves online, rather than as a fixed attribute of a person.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Researchers in the field study how those self-representations are influenced by platform design, audience, and the technical affordances available for self-presentation.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Sherry Turkle, in *Life on the Screen* (1995), argued that online environments allow users to present multiple, fluid versions of the self that are less anchored to physical embodiment than offline identity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Later scholarship has questioned how far this separation extends in practice, arguing that characteristics such as race, gender, and class continue to shape how users are perceived and treated online.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Clare Sullivan presents the grounds for digital identity as an emerging legal concept.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The UK's Identity Cards Act 2006 confirms Sullivan's argument and unfolds the new legal concept involving database identity and transaction identity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Database identity is the collection of data that is registered about an individual within the databases of the scheme and transaction identity is a set of information that defines the individual's identity for transactional purposes.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Although there is reliance on the verification of identity, none of the processes used are entirely trustworthy.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The consequences of digital identity abuse and fraud are potentially serious since in possible implications the person is held legally responsible.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Legal scholars Lusine Vardanyan, Ondrej Hamulak, and Hovsep Kocharyan from Palacký University in Olomouc have analyzed the complexities of digital identity and its regulation.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Their research highlights the difficulties that current legal frameworks face in adequately safeguarding digital identity against manipulation, unauthorized use, and opaque profiling mechanisms.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] They argue that existing data protection regimes predominantly focus on the protection of information rather than the individual as a whole, which may contribute to a loss of control over one's digital presence.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] A key concept proposed to address these issues is the right to informational self-determination, which would provide individuals with greater control over the collection, use, and dissemination of their personal data.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] This right is seen as essential in ensuring personal autonomy, enabling individuals to shape and manage their digital identities in alignment with their real-world personas.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Proponents argue that the development of legal tools for digital identity management should be grounded in principles such as informed consent, transparency, and self-governance.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] The work of scholars such as Shoshana Zuboff has been influential in highlighting the risks associated with the commodification of personal data and the erosion of individual agency in digital spaces.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Recognizing informational self-determination as a fundamental right is viewed as a critical step in enhancing data protection and ensuring security and autonomy in an increasingly networked society.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Corporations are recognizing the power of the internet to tailor their online presence to each individual customer.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Purchase suggestions, personalized adverts, and other tailored marketing strategies are a great success for businesses.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Such tailoring, however, depends on the ability to connect attributes and preferences to the identity of the visitor.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] As the internet becomes more attuned to privacy concerns, media publishers, application developers, and online retailers are re-evaluating their strategies, sometimes reinventing their business models completely.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Increasingly, the trend is shifting towards monetizing online offerings directly, with users being asked to pay for access through subscriptions and other forms of payment, moving away from the reliance on collecting personal data.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Digital death is the phenomenon of people continuing to have Internet accounts after their deaths.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] This results in several ethical issues concerning how the information stored by the deceased person may be used or stored or given to the family members.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] It also may result in confusion due to automated social media features such as birthday reminders, as well as uncertainty about the deceased person's willingness to pass their personal information to a third party.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Many social media platforms do not have clear policies about digital death.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Many companies secure digital identities after death or legally pass those on to the deceased people's families.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Some companies will also provide options for digital identity erasure after death.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Facebook/Meta is a clear-cut example of a company that provides digital options after death.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Descendants or friends of the deceased individual can let Facebook know about the death and have all of their previous digital activity removed.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Digital activity is but not limited to messages, photos, posts, comments, reactions, stories, archived history, etc.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Furthermore, the entire Facebook account will be deleted upon request.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] There are proponents of treating self-determination and freedom of expression of digital identity as a new human right.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Some have speculated that digital identities could become a new form of legal entity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] As technology develops so does the intelligence of certain digital identities, moving forward many believe that there should be more developments in legal aspects that regulate online presences and collection.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Digital identity can be a component to techno-authoritarianism.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] GDPR is one attempt to address this concern using the regulation.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] This regulation tactic was introduced by the European Union (EU) in 2018 for addressing concerns about the privacy and personal data of EU citizens.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] GDPR applies to all companies, regardless of location, that handle users within the EU.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Any company that collects, stores, and operates with data from EU citizens must disclose key details about the management of that data to EU individuals.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] EU citizens can also request for certain aspects of their collected data to be deleted.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Many systems provide privacy-related mitigations when analyzing data linked to digital identities.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] One common mitigation is data anonymization, such as hashing user identifiers with a cryptographic hash function.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Another popular technique is adding statistical noise to a data set to reduce identifiability, such as in differential privacy.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Although a digital identity allows consumers to transact from anywhere and more easily manage various ID cards, it also poses a potential single point of compromise that malicious hackers can use to steal all of that personal information.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Hence, several different account authentication methods have been created to protect users.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Initially, these authentication methods will require a setup from the user to enable these security features when attempting a login.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Although many facets of digital identity are universal owing in part to the ubiquity of the Internet, some regional variations exist due to specific laws, practices, and government services that are in place.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] For example, digital identity can use services that validate driving licences, passports, and other physical documents online to help improve the quality of a digital identity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Also, strict policies against money laundering mean that some services, such as money transfers, need a stricter level of validation of digital identity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/digital-identity] Digital identity in the national sense can mean a combination of single sign-on and/or validation of assertions by trusted authorities (generally the government).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] A **distributed ledger** (also called a **shared ledger** or **distributed ledger technology** or **DLT**) is a system whereby replicated, shared, and synchronized digital data is geographically spread (distributed) across many sites, countries, or institutions.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] In contrast to a centralized database, a distributed ledger does not require a central administrator, and consequently does not have a single (central) point-of-failure.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] In general, a distributed ledger requires a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network and consensus algorithms so that the ledger is reliably replicated across distributed computer nodes (servers, clients, etc.).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] The most common form of distributed ledger technology is the blockchain (commonly associated with cryptocurrency), which can either be on a public or private network.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] Infrastructure for data management is a common barrier to implementing DLT.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] Distributed ledger data is typically spread across multiple nodes (computational devices) on a P2P network, where each replicates and saves an identical copy of the ledger data and updates itself independently of other nodes.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] The primary advantage of this distributed processing pattern is the lack of a central authority, which would constitute a single point of failure.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] When a ledger update transaction is broadcast to the P2P network, each distributed node processes a new update transaction independently, and then collectively all working nodes use a consensus algorithm to determine the correct copy of the updated ledger.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] Once a consensus has been determined, all the other nodes update themselves with the latest, correct copy of the updated ledger.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] Security is enforced through cryptographic keys and signatures.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] Certificate Transparency is an Internet security standard for monitoring and auditing the issuance of digital certificates based on a distributed ledger.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] It was initiated in 2011, standardised in 2013 and started to be used by the Google Chrome browser for all certificates in 2018.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] In 2016, some banks tested distributed ledger systems for payments to determine their usefulness.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] In 2020, Axoni launched Veris, a distributed ledger platform that manages equity swap transactions.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] The platform, which matches and reconciles post-trade data on stock swaps, is used by BlackRock Inc., Goldman Sachs Group Inc., and Citigroup, Inc.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] A pilot scheme by the Monetary Authority of Singapore completed its first live trades using DLT in 2022.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] The pilot by Singapore's central bank involved JP Morgan, SBI Digital Asset Holdings and DBS.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] The banks traded using smart contracts against liquidity pools of tokenized Singapore government bonds, Japanese government bonds, yen, and Singapore dollars.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] Standard Chartered Bank is exploring tokens for trade finance; and HSBC and United Overseas Bank are working with Marketnode, a digital markets infrastructure provider, on products for wealth management.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] DLT can be used for smart contracting, which is the formation of contracts which automatically complete when triggered by prevailing conditions.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] DLT is itself secured by cryptographic methods, but can also be used as a base layer on which to build further cryptographic applications, such as protocols that require or benefit from a public broadcast mechanism, including transparent decryption.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] In the context of cryptocurrencies, distributed ledger technologies can be categorized in terms of their data structures, consensus algorithms, permissions, and whether they are mined.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] DLT data structure types include linear data structures (blockchains) to more complex directed acyclic graph (DAG) and hybrid data structures.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] DLT consensus algorithm types include proof-of-work (PoW) and proof-of-stake (PoS) algorithms and DAG consensus-building and voting algorithms.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] DLTs are generally either permissioned (private) or permissionless (public).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] PoW cryptocurrencies are generally either 'mined' or 'non-mined', where the latter typically indicates 'pre-mined' cryptocurrencies, such as XRP or IOTA.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] PoS cryptocurrencies do not use miners, instead usually relying on validation among owners of the cryptocurrency, such as Cardano or Solana.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] Blockchains are the most common DLT type, with a 256-bit secure hash algorithm (SHA).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] DLTs based on DAG data structures or hybrid blockchain-DAG decrease transaction data size and transaction costs, while increasing transaction speeds compared with bitcoin, the first cryptocurrency.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] Examples of DAG DLT cryptocurrencies include MIOTA (IOTA Tangle DLT) and HBAR (Hedera Hashgraph).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/distributed-ledger] Holochain represents a departure from traditional DLT models, using an agent-centric approach with individual source chains and a distributed hash table (DHT) for data validation, eliminating the need for a global consensus mechanism.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/identity-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The TCP/IP protocol provides identifiers for machines, but not for the people and organisations operating the machines.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Services provide identifiers for the user, not the network.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The absence of reliable identifiers is one of the primary sources of cybercrime, fraud, and threats to privacy on the internet.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] With the advent of blockchain technology, a new model for decentralized identity emerged in 2015.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The FIDO Alliance proposed an identity model that was no longer account-based, but identified people through direct, private, peer-to-peer connections secured by public/private key cryptography.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Self-Sovereign Identity (SSI) summarises all components of the decentralized identity model: digital wallets, digital credentials, and digital connections.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] SSI addresses the difficulty of establishing trust in an interaction.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] In order to be trusted, one party in an interaction will present credentials to the other parties, and those relying on the parties can verify that the credentials came from an issuer that they trust.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] In this way, the verifier's trust in the issuer is transferred to the credential holder.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] This basic structure of SSI with three participants is sometimes called "the trust triangle".
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] It is generally recognized that for an identity system to be self-sovereign, users control the verifiable credentials that they hold, and their consent is required to use those credentials.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] This reduces the unintended sharing of users' personal data.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] This is contrasted with the centralized identity paradigm where identity is provided by some outside entity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] In an SSI system, holders generate and control unique identifiers called decentralized identifiers.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Most SSI systems are decentralized, where the credentials are managed using crypto wallets and verified using public-key cryptography anchored on a distributed ledger.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The credentials may contain data from an issuer's database, a social media account, a history of transactions on an e-commerce site, or attestation from friends or colleagues.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Some blockchain identity systems use smart contracts as accounts with attachable data and permissions.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] ERC-725 is a draft Ethereum standard for smart-contract accounts with generic data storage and execution.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] LUKSO's Universal Profiles apply this model to on-chain profiles, combining a recoverable smart-contract account with public profile data for decentralized applications.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The European Union is exploring decentralized digital identity through a number of initiatives including the International Association for Trusted Blockchain Application (INATBA), the EU Blockchain Observatory & Forum and the European SSI Framework.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] In 2019, the EU created an eIDAS compatible European Self-Sovereign Identity Framework (ESSIF).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The ESSIF makes use of decentralized identifiers (DIDs) and the European Blockchain Services Infrastructure (EBSI).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The Korean government created a public/private consortium specifically for decentralized identity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] In the German and European legal area, there are two regulations that are of particular importance for the topic.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] These include the eIDAS Regulation, which forms the most important framework for trust in electronic identification in the EU and is a fundamental building block of the digital single market.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The European Blockchain Service Infrastructure (EBSI) has provided the SSI eIDAS Bridge, as a technical implementation that enables a substantial level of trust.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The eIDAS SSI legal report also describes several scenarios of how SSI can fulfill the necessary regulatory conditions.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Furthermore, the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) forms the legal basis for the handling of personal data.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The EBSI GDPR Legal Report provides more information on this.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] SSI is a value laden technology whose technical operationalizations differ (see Technical aspects).
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Therefore, its implementations can vary significantly and embed into the very technology different goals, agenda, and intentions.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The term "self-sovereign identity" can create expectations that individuals have absolute control and ownership over their digital identities, akin to physical possessions.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] However, in practice, SSI involves complex technical infrastructure, interactions with identity issuers and verifiers, and compliance with legal frameworks.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] The reality may not align with the perception generated by the term, leading to semantic confusion.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Critics argue that SSI may exacerbate social inequalities and exclude those with limited access to technology or digital literacy.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] SSI assumes reliable internet connectivity, access to compatible devices, and proficiency in navigating digital systems.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/self-sovereign-identity] Consequently, marginalized populations, including the elderly, individuals in developing regions, or those with limited technological resources, may face exclusion and reduced access to the benefits of SSI.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Verifiable credentials can be issued by anyone, about anything, and can be presented to and verified by everyone.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] The entity that generates the credential is called the *Issuer*.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] The credential is then given to the *Holder* who stores it for later use.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] The Holder can then prove something about themselves by presenting their credentials to a *Verifier*.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] The holder of a verifiable credential operates in a triangle of trust, mediating between issuer and verifier.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Any role in the triangle can be played by a person, an institution, or a machine.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Note that because verifiable credentials can be created by anyone, the verifier decides if they trust the issuer.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] The VC model places the holder of a credential at the center of the identity ecosystem, giving individuals control of their identity attributes.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] The W3C VC model parallels physical credentials: the user holds cards and can present them to anyone at any time without informing or requiring the permission of the card issuer.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Such a model is decentralized and gives much more autonomy and privacy to the participants.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] This contrasts with the federated identity management (FIM) model, as adopted by SAML and OpenID Connect, which place the identity provider (IdP) in the central role as the dispenser of identity attributes and the determiner of which Service Providers (SPs) it will give them to.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] In the federated model, the IdP knows every SP that the user visits.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] The data model for verifiable credentials is a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) Recommendation, "Verifiable Credentials Data Model 1.0 - Expressing verifiable information on the Web", published 19 November 2019.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] The VC context, defined using the `@context` JSON property, is a JSON-LD construct that allows user friendly terms to be used for JSON properties.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] According to the VC data model, the value of many properties must be a URI.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Whilst these are globally unambiguous, (important for a global data model), they are not user-friendly.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Consequently, the `@context` property allows short-form, user-friendly aliases to be defined for each URI.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] This makes it much easier, and more user-friendly, to specify VCs.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Any new property can be added to VCs, as determined by the issuer.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Standard properties have been defined specifically as extension points.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] The holder of a VC does not always have to be the subject of the credential.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] It is expected that most users will hold their own VCs, i.e., the holder and the subject will be the same entity.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] For example, when the VC subject is an infant, and the VC is a birth certificate, the holder may be one or both parents.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] No proof mechanism is standardized but the data model is flexible enough to support various existing cryptographic mechanisms, such as digital signatures.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Proof mechanisms that are in use include: JSON Web Tokens with JSON Web Signatures, JSON-LD proofs, and zero-knowledge proofs using schemes such as IBM's anonymous credentials.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Various protocols are specified for carrying VCs from the issuer/IdP to the holder, and the holder to the verifier.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] None of these protocols has become standardized.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Many people who are experimenting with VCs use HTTPS to carry VCs between the various parties.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] The security of verifiable credentials in the context of COVID-19 vaccination and test certificates has been questioned.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Verifiable credentials have also been subject to usability concerns.
[src:self-sovereign-identity/verifiable-credentials] Some have likened anyone being able to issue a verifiable credential being like a shop clerk deciding if they should accept an out-of-state license as proof of age when purchasing alcohol.
